From: jepler@nyx.cs.du.edu (Jeff Epler)
Subject: Re: 64K Vs 128K Cache:-is difference worth $40.00
Date: Wed, 25 Aug 93 17:42:03 GMT

[This message was originally posted in comp.os.msdos.misc.  It caught
my eye, and prompted a question]
[Sorry it's formatted so badly (>80 columns) but it's not really my
fault..]

In article <25eoqu$ap2@vail.levels.unisa.edu.au> ldurbrid@cssip.levels.unisa.edu.au (Lyndon Durbridge) writes:
[Attributions lost somewhere]
>>>
>>>       ... Is there any
>>>     noticable difference in throughput/speed between the 64K cache
>>>     and the 128K cache? Is it worth $40.00
>>> 
>>Devon,
>>
>>I just recently upgraded the cache on my 386DX40 from 64 to 128 KB as an experiment
>>in enhancing performance.  It improved performance a whopping 2 to 3 per cent. Not
>>worth the trouble in my judgement.  The difference between no cache and even a modest
>>one in terms of performance is tremendous (about a 50 to 150% speedup), so clearly
>>increasing the cache size beyond that first step is a game of (rapidly) diminishing
>>returns.  Save your money and get more RAM instead.  
>>
>>All in my own opinion of course.
>>
>>Richard 
>
>Pardon me, but I think you need to consider your applications too. Under DOS you
>probably won't find much of an improvement in increasing cache beyond 64k, but
>if you are running a memory hungry application such as Windows you will find a
>significant improvement. Basically, if the application fits into your cache then
>it will run much faster, so small programs only need a small cache.


If this is true for DOS vs Windows (You know, the one with the 16-bit
extender?), is it true for Linux?

I would expect that most caches wouldn't do a whole lot of good --
Wouldn't the data/code cached in them change a lot as the computer
changed from task to task?  

Has anyone benchmarked Linux comparing a cached motherboard with the
same non-cached motherboard, or with more cache ram? 

(I could find out some figures for my 386/40 with 64K cache vs. the
cache turned off.  Under DOS benchmarks it seems to make a big
diference.)


--
Jeff Epler jepler@nyx.cs.du.edu (Preferred) or bx304@cleveland.freenet.edu
