From: dnewcomb@cybernet.cse.fau.edu (Dan Newcombe)
Subject: Re: Linux and Corporate America
Date: Wed, 25 Aug 1993 18:12:16 GMT

rick@ee.uwm.edu (Rick Miller - Linux Device Registrar) writes:
> 
>       Linus, have you *paid* for your Copyright on Linux yet?
>       It has been openly published for over a year now...
> 

So what is being said here is that if Linus doesn't hand over some money
to some governement (or is it the Free Software Foundation) that the
material is not his, he didn't write it, he didn't create it?  I don't
think so.

Like I posted in another newsgroup today, I believe when copyrights came out
they were to protect authors of material from being plagarised by someone.
You know, so I couldn't take Linus's code, claim it was mine, and then 
try to take credit for it.  The @#$@# government and it's stupid little
courts and lawyers have taken this and twisted it into something even harder
to understand than the GPL.  Copyright means about anything nowadays.
My personal fave is "intelectual property."  Screw AT&T...that's the dumbest
thing I've ever heard of.  But I digress...

On the original topic, I am a little bit confused.  I know the GLP says
that if something is sold that has been GPL'd, then you must make the
source available, or tell how to get it (ftp, etc...)  But what if
Company XYZ did some work on it, beefed it up, lets say added the real
time support needed for the nuclear core monitoringg (This brings a whole
new meaning to the Core Dumped messages :)  So with this new code, under the
GPL that Linux has, what do they have to make available??? All of the code,
only the Linux source code???

While I do like the FSF and think that the GPL is a good idea, they need
a translator to take the thing and put it in English (not the Lawyerish it
is in.)

   Dan (I'm gonna copyright the word 'the' and sue everyone :)

