From: mark@taylor.uucp (Mark A. Davis)
Subject: Re: Linux and Corporate America
Date: Wed, 25 Aug 1993 18:20:46 GMT

hawley@ucrengr.ucr.edu (brian hawley) writes:



>Some fellow graduate students and I were discussing the distribution
>of Linux.  One of the questions that came up was what would prevent
>a company from adding some enhancements to Linux and then selling it
>for a price. 

There is nothing to prevent this, and I think some do.  You do have to
consider the GPL on the OS, though.

> It might even be that Linux is used just as an OS on
>some integrated system which provided the ability to sense a nuclear
>reactor mealtdown and lower the rods (please don't flame about the
>real time nature of Linux and this application, it is just an example).

I doubt there will be a great commercial interest until Linux is binary
compatible (fully) with other 386 Unixes (COFF/ELF).  At that point, much
business software will work under Linux.  And when that happens, I can see
great market potential.  Another approach is a VAR who can have their
key piece of software ported to Linux and then bundle Linux as the OS
for their product platform.

Let me pull a real-world example out of the air:  I have a friend who works
at a car shop and would like to trash their toy MS-"DOS" system for something
more realistic (multiuser, email, multi-terminals & printers, etc...).
There are at least 4 good Unix packages for Automotive shops available under
standard SCO Unix (COFF).  They are, however (being so small), very cost
sensitive.  Buying the Auto package AND SCO is still a little too high
(for their expected 4-5 user system setup).  If Linux could run the
many thousands of packages SCO can, then it could be used in the above
example to perhaps reduce the system cost by $1500+, making it more affordable.

>What restrictions are placed on the distribution of Linux, and its
>reuse in other products.  

I will let others elaborate.  But if modifications are made to the OS, they
would be covered by the GPL and must enter into the GPL also.  I don't think
this is true if they are add-on's (such as value added programs and such)-
those could be copyrighted by the vendor.  Otherwise, (besides GPL
stipulations), there are no distribution restrictions.

